  <body>
    <div style="basic">
        <p begin="00:00:00" end="00:00:02.10" tts:direction="ltr">Hi, Data 2,100 students.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:02.10" end="00:00:07.2" tts:direction="ltr">In this video, we are going to learn how
<br/>to do multitable queries.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:07.2" end="00:00:10.4" tts:direction="ltr">We also often term these joins.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:10.4" end="00:00:12.7" tts:direction="ltr">Now, before the video right here at the
<br/>beginning,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:12.7" end="00:00:14.5" tts:direction="ltr">make sure that you launch beekeeper,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:14.5" end="00:00:18.10" tts:direction="ltr">and then you download the examples file
<br/>that I have provided for you.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:18.10" end="00:00:22.2" tts:direction="ltr">We've talked a lot in this class about</p>
        <p begin="00:00:22.2" end="00:00:26.8" tts:direction="ltr">relational databases and how database
<br/>tables relate to one another.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:26.8" end="00:00:28.7" tts:direction="ltr">But previous to this video,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:28.7" end="00:00:31.8" tts:direction="ltr">we've only queried one database table at a
<br/>time.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:31.8" end="00:00:33.8" tts:direction="ltr">We're not really taking into account</p>
        <p begin="00:00:33.8" end="00:00:37.1" tts:direction="ltr">how different tables relate to each other.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:37.1" end="00:00:39.2" tts:direction="ltr">In this video, we're going to learn about,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:39.2" end="00:00:43.4" tts:direction="ltr">how can we actually harness the power of a
<br/>relational database?</p>
        <p begin="00:00:43.4" end="00:00:44.10" tts:direction="ltr">Let's go ahead and do that.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:44.10" end="00:00:47.9" tts:direction="ltr">So our video objectives here are to learn
<br/>how</p>
        <p begin="00:00:47.9" end="00:00:50.7" tts:direction="ltr">to query multiple tables at once.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:50.7" end="00:00:53.5" tts:direction="ltr">Let's talk about a multiple table query.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:53.5" end="00:00:56.6" tts:direction="ltr">Again, this is in our query,</p>
        <p begin="00:00:56.6" end="00:00:59.3" tts:direction="ltr">we are going to be querying from more than
<br/>one table.</p>
        <p begin="00:00:59.3" end="00:01:03.1" tts:direction="ltr">We're going to be using the power of a
<br/>relational database.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:03.1" end="00:01:06.6" tts:direction="ltr">Often the query columns we would like to
<br/>return</p>
        <p begin="00:01:06.6" end="00:01:10.6" tts:direction="ltr">exist in different yet related tables.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:10.6" end="00:01:14.8" tts:direction="ltr">We want to know guest information and we
<br/>want to know household information.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:14.8" end="00:01:16.7" tts:direction="ltr">That's in two different tables.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:16.7" end="00:01:21" tts:direction="ltr">Oftentimes, we want to return columns from
<br/>both of the tables,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:21" end="00:01:24.6" tts:direction="ltr">we need to be able to harness the power of
<br/>relational database to do that.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:24.6" end="00:01:27.9" tts:direction="ltr">So to return columns from multiple tables,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:27.9" end="00:01:30.4" tts:direction="ltr">we join the tables in the query,</p>
        <p begin="00:01:30.4" end="00:01:33.6" tts:direction="ltr">effectively creating a new virtual table</p>
        <p begin="00:01:33.6" end="00:01:36.8" tts:direction="ltr">that combines the data from both tables.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:36.8" end="00:01:39.4" tts:direction="ltr">Joins may be performed implicitly</p>
        <p begin="00:01:39.4" end="00:01:42.2" tts:direction="ltr">or explicitly in a query. We'll talk about
<br/>that.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:42.2" end="00:01:45.7" tts:direction="ltr">Let's take a look here. I'm going to look
<br/>at Facebook, LinkedIn.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:45.7" end="00:01:48.6" tts:direction="ltr">I have a Facebook table and I have a
<br/>LinkedIn table.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:48.6" end="00:01:53.9" tts:direction="ltr">This is one table or entity and another
<br/>table LinkedIn.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:53.9" end="00:01:56.10" tts:direction="ltr">I have these two different tables.</p>
        <p begin="00:01:56.10" end="00:02:02.3" tts:direction="ltr">In this, I am tracking my different, we'll
<br/>take a look here.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:02.3" end="00:02:07.2" tts:direction="ltr">Um, I'm tracking my different connections
<br/>on Facebook and on LinkedIn.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:07.2" end="00:02:09.1" tts:direction="ltr">I have an ID here of John,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:09.1" end="00:02:12.5" tts:direction="ltr">birthday 55 of 2000 married,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:12.5" end="00:02:15.3" tts:direction="ltr">and then over here, I have, let's see
<br/>here,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:15.3" end="00:02:19.9" tts:direction="ltr">ID number four is Amy, Facebook,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:19.9" end="00:02:24.1" tts:direction="ltr">birthday is 1999, and married and same
<br/>thing over here,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:24.1" end="00:02:28.8" tts:direction="ltr">I have Amy, their employers eBay and their
<br/>department is marketing.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:28.8" end="00:02:32.4" tts:direction="ltr">What I'm looking at these two tables here,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:32.4" end="00:02:37.5" tts:direction="ltr">these IDs are uniquely identifying these
<br/>people.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:37.5" end="00:02:39.8" tts:direction="ltr">I want to show the name,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:39.8" end="00:02:42.6" tts:direction="ltr">the birthday, the marital status,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:42.6" end="00:02:48.10" tts:direction="ltr">employer and Department of Common
<br/>Connections on Facebook and LinkedIn.</p>
        <p begin="00:02:48.10" end="00:02:52.5" tts:direction="ltr">That's my question that I want to answer
<br/>here is I want to look at,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:52.5" end="00:02:54.2" tts:direction="ltr">if I have a common connection that has</p>
        <p begin="00:02:54.2" end="00:02:57.8" tts:direction="ltr">a Facebook account and a common connection
<br/>that has a LinkedIn account,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:57.8" end="00:02:59.10" tts:direction="ltr">if I want to return all of their
<br/>information,</p>
        <p begin="00:02:59.10" end="00:03:02.2" tts:direction="ltr">how do I go about doing them?</p>
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          <p begin="00:03:02.3" end="00:03:07.1" tts:direction="ltr">The first thing that I'm going to do is I
<br/>want to identify the tables that</p>
        <p begin="00:03:07.1" end="00:03:11.9" tts:direction="ltr">contain the desired data for the from
<br/>clause.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:11.9" end="00:03:15.9" tts:direction="ltr">Now we're going to use table aliases for
<br/>convenience,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:15.9" end="00:03:17.7" tts:direction="ltr">so I'll talk about this in just a second.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:17.7" end="00:03:20.2" tts:direction="ltr">Again, these two tables are related.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:20.2" end="00:03:23.10" tts:direction="ltr">We can see here that Amy ID number four,
<br/>this Amy,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:23.10" end="00:03:25.3" tts:direction="ltr">and this Amy are the same,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:25.3" end="00:03:28.6" tts:direction="ltr">and I want to return their information to
<br/>me.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:28.6" end="00:03:32.6" tts:direction="ltr">I want to know all of my Facebook and
<br/>LinkedIn connections.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:32.6" end="00:03:35.6" tts:direction="ltr">If they have a Facebook and they have a
<br/>LinkedIn,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:35.6" end="00:03:37.7" tts:direction="ltr">I want them to return to me and my output.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:37.7" end="00:03:41.1" tts:direction="ltr">I want to show the name, birthday, marital
<br/>status,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:41.1" end="00:03:45.9" tts:direction="ltr">employer and Department of Common
<br/>Connections on Facebook and LinkedIn.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:45.9" end="00:03:49.5" tts:direction="ltr">First off, I'm going to identify the
<br/>tables that contain the desired data.</p>
        <p begin="00:03:49.5" end="00:03:54.9" tts:direction="ltr">Let's take a look at this. I'm going to in
<br/>my from clause,</p>
        <p begin="00:03:54.9" end="00:04:00.1" tts:direction="ltr">I'm going to say from Facebook as F. I get
<br/>a mini alias here.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:00.1" end="00:04:02.2" tts:direction="ltr">This is just for convenience.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:02.2" end="00:04:05.8" tts:direction="ltr">When we continue to query our tables,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:05.8" end="00:04:09.4" tts:direction="ltr">we're going to refer to this new alias of</p>
        <p begin="00:04:09.4" end="00:04:14.6" tts:direction="ltr">F. Instead of having to type out the
<br/>entire table name of Facebook.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:14.6" end="00:04:20.1" tts:direction="ltr">Same thing with LinkedIn as L. I'm joining
<br/>these two tables.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:20.1" end="00:04:25.10" tts:direction="ltr">Facebook is F, join LinkedIn as L. That's
<br/>what I do first off.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:25.10" end="00:04:29.1" tts:direction="ltr">Now, step two, I'm going to identify the
<br/>common column,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:29.1" end="00:04:34.3" tts:direction="ltr">the primary foreign key shared between
<br/>tables for the on clause.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:34.3" end="00:04:37" tts:direction="ltr">Now, remember the column name does not
<br/>matter,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:37" end="00:04:39.8" tts:direction="ltr">just that the columns contain the same
<br/>data.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:39.8" end="00:04:43.4" tts:direction="ltr">This is the column on which the tables are
<br/>joined.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:43.4" end="00:04:48.5" tts:direction="ltr">Now when I run this or when I want to use
<br/>my on clause,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:48.5" end="00:04:55.1" tts:direction="ltr">I see here that I have My ID field and my
<br/>ID field a Facebook and LinkedIn.</p>
        <p begin="00:04:55.1" end="00:04:57.10" tts:direction="ltr">I can see here that Janet, Amy,</p>
        <p begin="00:04:57.10" end="00:05:01.6" tts:direction="ltr">and Kevin are common connections between
<br/>both.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:01.6" end="00:05:04.6" tts:direction="ltr">John and Kim don't have a LinkedIn</p>
        <p begin="00:05:04.6" end="00:05:07.8" tts:direction="ltr">or not a common connection and Steve and
<br/>Lisa,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:07.8" end="00:05:09.4" tts:direction="ltr">I'm LinkedIn connected to them,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:09.4" end="00:05:11.6" tts:direction="ltr">but I'm not Facebook connected to them.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:11.6" end="00:05:16.6" tts:direction="ltr">Only these three are my common connections
<br/>that I have on Facebook.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:16.6" end="00:05:18.8" tts:direction="ltr">And on LinkedIn and that are in</p>
        <p begin="00:05:18.8" end="00:05:21.5" tts:direction="ltr">my Facebook table and are in my LinkedIn
<br/>table.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:21.5" end="00:05:24.8" tts:direction="ltr">What I do here is I add on the on clause,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:24.8" end="00:05:29.8" tts:direction="ltr">again, which says this is F dot ID.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:29.8" end="00:05:33.8" tts:direction="ltr">This is the ID that needs to be equal to
<br/>the L dot ID,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:33.8" end="00:05:39.4" tts:direction="ltr">meaning This is the column on which tables
<br/>are joined.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:39.4" end="00:05:44.3" tts:direction="ltr">The column name does not matter just that
<br/>the columns contain the same data.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:44.3" end="00:05:50.6" tts:direction="ltr">We are saying that only return to me
<br/>records of which the f dot,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:50.6" end="00:05:54.6" tts:direction="ltr">the Facebook dot ID is equal to the
<br/>LinkedIn dot ID.</p>
        <p begin="00:05:54.6" end="00:05:58.1" tts:direction="ltr">Perfect. Now the next thing I need to do
<br/>is step three,</p>
        <p begin="00:05:58.1" end="00:06:01.5" tts:direction="ltr">we're going to add desired columns to
<br/>select clause.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:01.5" end="00:06:06.2" tts:direction="ltr">Use table names and aliases as prefix for
<br/>ambiguous columns.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:06.2" end="00:06:10.3" tts:direction="ltr">Ambiguous columns are columns that exist
<br/>in both tables,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:10.3" end="00:06:12.5" tts:direction="ltr">and we'll talk more about that in a bit.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:12.5" end="00:06:16.10" tts:direction="ltr">So here, hint, start with select star to
<br/>see all columns from both tables.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:16.10" end="00:06:18.2" tts:direction="ltr">That's what we'll start with.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:18.2" end="00:06:20.5" tts:direction="ltr">But here, as I want to show the name,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:20.5" end="00:06:22.3" tts:direction="ltr">the birthday, the marital status,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:22.3" end="00:06:24" tts:direction="ltr">and the employer and department,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:24" end="00:06:25.9" tts:direction="ltr">I see here that I return the name,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:25.9" end="00:06:27.6" tts:direction="ltr">the birthday, the marital status,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:27.6" end="00:06:29" tts:direction="ltr">the employer, and the department.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:29" end="00:06:34.6" tts:direction="ltr">I select all of the columns that I want to
<br/>see from this mult able query.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:34.6" end="00:06:37.3" tts:direction="ltr">Now, you'll notice here that name,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:37.3" end="00:06:41.8" tts:direction="ltr">birthday, and marital status is all coming
<br/>from birthday.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:41.8" end="00:06:44.4" tts:direction="ltr">Now, name exists in both tables,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:44.4" end="00:06:46.8" tts:direction="ltr">which is an ambiguous column,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:46.8" end="00:06:49.2" tts:direction="ltr">meaning it exists in both tables.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:49.2" end="00:06:55.4" tts:direction="ltr">I need to specify using my handy alias I
<br/>just created to say F dot name.</p>
        <p begin="00:06:55.4" end="00:06:59.5" tts:direction="ltr">This means pull the name from the Facebook
<br/>table,</p>
        <p begin="00:06:59.5" end="00:07:03.5" tts:direction="ltr">then birthday and marital status and then
<br/>employer and department.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:03.5" end="00:07:08.5" tts:direction="ltr">Here I'm selecting this information from
<br/>this multi able query.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:08.5" end="00:07:13.4" tts:direction="ltr">And the records that are going to return
<br/>to me are Janet,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:13.4" end="00:07:16.2" tts:direction="ltr">Amy, and Kevin's records.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:16.2" end="00:07:18.9" tts:direction="ltr">Specifically, their name, their birthday,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:18.9" end="00:07:23.2" tts:direction="ltr">their marital status, their employer and
<br/>the department will return to me.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:23.2" end="00:07:29.5" tts:direction="ltr">Perfect. Awesome. We'll notice here this
<br/>will be my result.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:29.5" end="00:07:31.3" tts:direction="ltr">The proposed query again, name,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:31.3" end="00:07:34.2" tts:direction="ltr">birthday, marital status, employer, and
<br/>department.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:34.2" end="00:07:37.1" tts:direction="ltr">This is what's going to return to me once
<br/>I run this query.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:37.1" end="00:07:41.1" tts:direction="ltr">The result will be the name from Facebook
<br/>table,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:41.1" end="00:07:42.9" tts:direction="ltr">the birthday, the marital status,</p>
        <p begin="00:07:42.9" end="00:07:44.5" tts:direction="ltr">the employer, and the department.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:44.5" end="00:07:49.2" tts:direction="ltr">Now I am capturing data from my Facebook
<br/>table and my LinkedIn table.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:49.2" end="00:07:52.4" tts:direction="ltr">We can see this right here from my
<br/>Facebook table and</p>
        <p begin="00:07:52.4" end="00:07:58.2" tts:direction="ltr">my LinkedIn table together is bringing me
<br/>this result right down here.</p>
        <p begin="00:07:58.2" end="00:08:06" tts:direction="ltr">Perfect. So the only rows that were
<br/>included are Janet, Amy, and Kevin.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:06" end="00:08:10.3" tts:direction="ltr">The only rows with matching values in the
<br/>joined column,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:10.3" end="00:08:12.9" tts:direction="ltr">the joined column was three, four and
<br/>five.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:12.9" end="00:08:15.6" tts:direction="ltr">In both tables will be returned,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:15.6" end="00:08:18.1" tts:direction="ltr">three, four and five were the only ones
<br/>that were matching.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:18.1" end="00:08:22.7" tts:direction="ltr">One and two and six and seven were not
<br/>matching.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:22.7" end="00:08:25.3" tts:direction="ltr">They didn't exist in both tables.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:25.3" end="00:08:32.7" tts:direction="ltr">Perfect. Rows without matching values are
<br/>excluded from the result output.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:32.7" end="00:08:38.1" tts:direction="ltr">If I come back here, you'll notice we're
<br/>only returning Janet, Amy, and Kevin.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:38.1" end="00:08:41.3" tts:direction="ltr">Perfect. This is called an inner join,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:41.3" end="00:08:47.2" tts:direction="ltr">which means that only data that's columns
<br/>match,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:47.2" end="00:08:48.8" tts:direction="ltr">the three, four and five,</p>
        <p begin="00:08:48.8" end="00:08:54.1" tts:direction="ltr">the matching values in the joined column
<br/>are returned to me in an inner join.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:54.1" end="00:08:55.10" tts:direction="ltr">This is called an inner join.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:55.10" end="00:08:58" tts:direction="ltr">It is the most common.</p>
        <p begin="00:08:58" end="00:09:02.3" tts:direction="ltr">Type of join or mult table query that we
<br/>will do.</p>
        <p begin="00:09:02.3" end="00:09:06.10" tts:direction="ltr">Other types of joins can be used to modify
<br/>this behavior.</p>
        <p begin="00:09:06.10" end="00:09:12.3" tts:direction="ltr">I also want to let you know that there's
<br/>two different types of joins.</p>
        <p begin="00:09:12.3" end="00:09:15.7" tts:direction="ltr">There's an implicit join and there's an
<br/>explicit join.</p>
        <p begin="00:09:15.7" end="00:09:23.5" tts:direction="ltr">The implicit join is a syntax that was
<br/>used more historically, if you will.</p>
        <p begin="00:09:23.5" end="00:09:29.10" tts:direction="ltr">It is not the standard today given its
<br/>limitations with other types of joins.</p>
        <p begin="00:09:29.10" end="00:09:33.4" tts:direction="ltr">The explicit join is what we will use in
